ifficult-to-reach population, the authors privilege the voices of brothel workers throughout the book as they reflect on their struggles to engage in their communities, conduct business, maintain personal relationships, and transition out of the industry. Further, the authors examine how these brothels operate like other kinds of legal entities, and how individuals contend with balancing work and non-work commitments, navigate work place cultures, and handle managerial relationships. Sex and Stigma serves as a resource on the policies guiding legal prostitution in Nevada and provides an intimate look at the lived experiences of women performing sex work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBrothels-Nevada. 0aProstitution-Nevada. 0aSex-Nevada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Prostitution & Sex Trade.2bisacsh  aNevada.  aPriscilla Varner.  aautoethnography.  abrothels.  acollaborative data analysis.  acommunicative constitution of organizations.  adirty work.  aethnographic methods.  afaculty-student collaboration.  afeminism.  ahidden organizations.  aimage management.  alabor discrimination.  alife story interview.  anegotiation.  aphoto elicitation.  aprivacy.  aprostitution.  aqualitative methods.  arevelation-concealment.  asecrecy.  asex trafficking.  asex work.  asocial support.  astandpoint theory.  atape dumps.  atrafficking.  atransferable skills.  awork-life balance.1 aMohr, Breanna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWolfe, Anna Wiederhold, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479859290.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479875597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479875597/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_E